CD (Continuous Delivery/Deployment) automates: 


Continuous Delivery is not equal to Continuous Deployment. 


	- Environment Provisioning
		○ Dev, QA, Prod 
	- Deployment to Dev, QA or Prod etc. 
	- Rollbacks. 


Real - world example: 

A fintech company uses: 

	1. ArgoCD for GitOps based deployments. 
	2. Helm Charts for Kubernetes deployments. 

CD Ensures fast, safe, repeatable releases. 


Continuous Delivery 

Code changes are built, tested, and prepared for releases BUT a human must manually trigger the final deployment to production. 

	- Automated: Build -- Test -- Staging  etc 
	- Manual: Push to production (requires approval) 

	GOAL: Ensure the code is always in a deployable state. 
	
	Best For: Teams that need business sign-off, compliance checks, or controlled release windows. 
	
	

Continuous Deployment

Every change that passes all automated tests is automatically deployed to production -- No human intervention at any stage. 


	- Automated: Build. --> Test -- Staging --> Production
	- No Manual approval - window is required to perform deployment to production. 


	GOAL: Ship to users as fast as possible with zero manual steps 

	Best For: Mature teams with high test coverage and fast rollback capabilities.
	
	
	
	How they fit in the CI/CD Pipeline: 
	
	
	Code Commit
	
	Continuous Integration (CO) 
		--> Build --> Unit Tests --> Integration tests
		
	Continuous Delivery (CD) 
		--> Deploy to staging --> Acceptance tests --> [Manual Approval] --> Production. 
		
	Continuous Deployment (CD) 
		--> Deploy to staging --> Acceptance Tests --> [Auto] -- Production
		
		
		
	Continuous Deployment is a superset of continuous Delivery. 
	
	All continuous Deployment pipelines practice continuous Delivery, but not vice-versa. 
	
	
	The only difference is whether a human clicks the final "deploy" button.
	
	
	



